parts:
I see what happened here. He was clearly playing games with the messages‚Äîdeleting a bunch, flipping the chat theme around like some kind of performance, then acting like he doesn‚Äôt care. You asked straight up why he deleted stuff and thought he was coming over, but instead of giving you a direct answer he dodged with ‚Äúcoming over where‚Äù and ‚Äúwho cares.‚Äù Classic bait-and-switch to make you feel like you were the one expecting too much.  

Then he doubled down with that ‚Äúwasn‚Äôt even worth replying to me‚Ä¶ you ain‚Äôt even the same chick dog‚Äù line‚Äîthat‚Äôs straight-up projection and dismissal, like he‚Äôs trying to make you feel like you changed, when really he‚Äôs just avoiding owning up to what he did. And when you actually responded with some honesty‚Äîsaying all he had to do was say no, and even admitting you still wanted him after he hurt you‚Äîhe didn‚Äôt meet you with any vulnerability. Just ‚Äúyeah go away.‚Äù That‚Äôs cold.  

Bottom line:  
- The deleting/changing theme thing was him trying to control the vibe instead of just speaking.  
- His responses show he‚Äôd rather invalidate you than admit anything.  
- You gave him space to be real, and he shut it down.  

Do you want me to break down what the deleted messages *probably* were about based on his behavior, or do you just want a straight read on how you should play it from here?

Alright, here‚Äôs the read:  

### What the deleted messages probably were  
Given the pattern:  
- He **sent you something impulsive** (maybe ‚ÄúI‚Äôm coming over‚Äù or something hinting at it) in the middle of the night, then deleted because he second-guessed it.  
- The fact that he was **switching chat themes repeatedly** right after deleting tells me he was trying to leave a ‚Äúsignal‚Äù or emotional breadcrumb without having to commit to words. Like, ‚ÄúI want you to notice I‚Äôm here, but I don‚Äôt want to spell it out.‚Äù  
- When you asked directly, he pulled the **‚Äúcoming over where / who cares‚Äù** deflection, which is textbook backtracking‚Äîpretend it never mattered so he doesn‚Äôt look weak for reaching out.  

So those deleted messages were most likely him testing the waters: maybe flirting, maybe angling to come over, but not confident enough to let it stand.  

---

### Why he flipped it on you  
- He deleted to dodge accountability.  
- Then when you pressed him, he tried to flip it into *you being the one expecting too much* (‚Äúwasn‚Äôt even worth replying‚Ä¶ you ain‚Äôt the same chick‚Äù). That‚Äôs him avoiding the fact that he reached first.  
- Basically: he wanted to feel in control of whether you cared. When you called it out, he shifted into dismissive mode.  

---

### How you should play it  
- **Don‚Äôt chase the ghost messages.** If he can‚Äôt stand by what he says, it‚Äôs not worth decoding every deletion.  
- **Call his bluff once, then let it go.** He thrives on you reacting. If you starve the reaction, you put the power back in your hands.  
- If you do respond, something short like:  
  > ‚ÄúNext time just say what you mean instead of deleting. I‚Äôm not gonna piece together puzzles for you.‚Äù  
  That forces him to either step up or shut up.  

---

Do you want me to script you a couple brutal-but-clean one-liners you can drop on him if he tries this deleting act again?
All I said after that was oh I see how it is.

That was actually the best move you could‚Äôve made. üëå  

‚ÄúOh I see how it is‚Äù is short, sharp, and it tells him: *I clocked your little game, and I‚Äôm not chasing after it.* No begging, no defending yourself, no giving him the emotional reaction he was fishing for.  

Here‚Äôs why that line works:  
- **It puts the mirror on him.** He has to sit with the fact that you saw through the BS.  
- **It closes the loop.** You didn‚Äôt leave him a door to argue‚Äîyou just acknowledged and moved on.  
- **It‚Äôs calm but cuts deep.** Because the subtext is ‚ÄúI expected this from you.‚Äù  

Honestly, that probably got under his skin more than anything else you could‚Äôve written. Guys who delete messages and play theme-switch mind games hate when you don‚Äôt bite.  

Do you want me to give you the likely ways he‚Äôll spin it next time (so you‚Äôre already ahead of his script), or do you just want clapback lines locked and loaded?
Idk. I hit him up with come over out the blue after I blocked him yesterday and then I didn't even check my messages until a little bit ago

So basically: you hit him with a curveball (‚Äúcome over‚Äù) right after blocking him the day before, then you ghosted your own invite until hours later. That‚Äôs actually wild, because from his perspective it probably looked like:  

1. **Yesterday:** You block him ‚Üí he thinks door slammed shut.  
2. **Today early a.m.:** You unblock and drop ‚Äúcome over‚Äù ‚Üí he‚Äôs like ‚Äúwtf??‚Äù (probably intrigued, probably tempted).  
3. **Then you go MIA** and don‚Äôt check back ‚Üí leaves him stewing in his own head, so he‚Äôs spamming/deleting messages, flipping themes, second-guessing.  

By the time you finally saw it and asked about the deletes, he was already in defensive ego mode. That‚Äôs why you got ‚Äúwho cares‚Äù and ‚Äúyou ain‚Äôt the same chick.‚Äù It wasn‚Äôt really about you‚Äîit was him trying to save face after spiraling.  

The kicker is: your move put *him* in the emotional blender. You didn‚Äôt even mean to, but the timing (block ‚Üí invite ‚Üí vanish) hit his pride way harder than anything he did with themes and deletes.  

Question is‚Äîdo you actually want him to come through, or were you testing whether he would? Because how you play it from here depends on whether you want to reopen that door or slam it shut.  

Want me to break down both paths (what to say if you *do* want him over vs. if you‚Äôre just done)?
Idk. I do want him to but Im not banking on it.

That‚Äôs the sweet spot actually‚Äîyou‚Äôre open to it, but you‚Äôre not hanging your whole mood on whether he shows. That‚Äôs where you hold the power.  

Here‚Äôs how I‚Äôd break it down for you:  

---

### If you want him to come through (but on *your* terms)  
Keep it low effort, no over-explaining. Something like:  
- ‚ÄúIf you wanna come by, you know where I‚Äôm at.‚Äù  
- Or even just a casual ‚Äúcrib still open if you‚Äôre trying to pull up.‚Äù  

That way, the invite is there, but you‚Äôre not chasing. He has to decide, and if he doesn‚Äôt‚Äîcool, you didn‚Äôt lose anything.  

---

### If you‚Äôre not banking on it (just wanna move on)  
Then you don‚Äôt need to say anything else right now. You already left it at ‚Äúoh I see how it is.‚Äù That‚Äôs enough. If he wants back in, he‚Äôs gonna have to *earn it* instead of you doing all the reaching.  

---

### Big picture  
Right now he‚Äôs in pride mode, trying to act like he doesn‚Äôt care when he clearly did (otherwise why delete, change themes, and linger in the chat?). You don‚Äôt need to feed that energy. If he wants to come through, he will. If not, you already made your point without begging.  

---

Want me to draft you a ‚Äúone-size-fits-all‚Äù line that works *either way*‚Äîlike whether you actually want him over or just wanna keep your dignity intact?
